496.commentText:
This project teaches you the basics of controlling AI through Flowgraph. 
Checkout the different flowgraphs for examples on how to interact with AI through
Flowgraph.
Hit play to see the AI in action.

253.description: This graphs shows how the AI can also control the player's vehicle.
253.name: Player Chase

message.value: The "AI Chase" node is controlling your car!

287.commentText:
To let the AI take control of the player's vehicle, you just pass the vehicleId to an
AI node (in this case the "AI  Chase" node).
When the AI is activated on the player's node, the player automatically
loses control of the vehicle and the AI takes over.

494.commentText:
You may want to modify the general behaviour of the AI of a vehicle. 
For this you can use the "AI Parameters" node, which gives you access to different options
for the AI like risk and speed.
The "AI Parameters" node has to be triggered only once to work.

260.description: This is the description for graph New State
260.name: AI Directly to

message.value: Now the "AI Directly To" node is controlling your car!

491.commentText:
Sometimes you only want the AI to drive to a specifc point in the world. 
An easy way to achieve this is the "AI Directly To" node, which takes a vec3 for the world position.
Because driving to a specific point at full speed can often result in not actually reaching that point, because of the environment or traffic,
it is better to set a target velocity for the AI, if the vehicle needs to arrive safely.

304.description: This graph disables the AI and ends the level.
304.name: End State

495.commentText: To disable the AI on a vehicle, you can use the "AI Disable" node and simply pass\nit the vehicleId.

316.description: This is the description for graph New State
316.name: AI Chase

490.commentText: To create a vehicle that chases another vehicle simply pass the Ids of the vehicle to the AI Chase node.\nThe vehicle will continue chasing even after it has "caught up" to the other vehicle.

323.description: This graphs shows how to use the "AI Arrive" node.
323.name: AI Arrive

message.value: Now the "AI Arrive" node is controlling your car

492.commentText:
The previously used "AI Directly To" node can cause many problems, especially if you
just want your AI to use the roads that are on the map and arrive safely.
For this the "AI Arrive" node is the right choice. You can define the waypoint it should drive to
in the world and the AI will take a mostly safe path and arrive at the location.

To set a waypoint for the AI, follow these steps in the World Editor:
- Open the "Main Toolbar"
- Press the "Create Object" button
- Press "BeamNG" in the "Toolbar2" that opened up
- Press the "Waypoint" button to create a waypoint in the world

You can also define what distance and what velocity the vehicle needs to have to be
 considered "arrived" at the waypoint.

376.description: This is the description for graph New State
376.name: AI Follow Path

message.value: The "AI Follow Path" node is controlling the car!

493.commentText:
Being able to lead the AI to a certain waypoint in the world with the "AI Arrive" node is certainly useful, but many times
you want to accomplish more complex or realistic behaviours.
For this there is the "AI Follow Path" node which is tightly linked with the ScriptAIManager system.
The idea is simple: You record a path by driving it yourself, that path is stored and the AI follows it.
To access the ScriptAIManager select the "Stored AI Path" node and press "Open ScriptAIManager" or you can
find it in the World Editor under "Window"->"Gameplay"->"Script AI Manager".

Here you see an overview of all vehicles in the level right now. To record a vehicle simply press the "Record" button for it.
At this point you should take control of the car and record your path. After you are done recording the path press "Stop Recording".
You can now either use the "Stored AI Path" node to store the path and pass it to the AI
or you can store the path as a file and use the "AI Path from File" node to pass it to the AI.

If you want to control the speed of how fast the AI follows the path, you can change the "Timescale" in the "AI Follow Path" node.
When using the "Stored AI Path" node and having the path loaded, you can view the path in the level while having the node selected.
493.commentTitle: Letting the AI follow a Path

500.commentText: When working with the AI, you may want some insights into the systems of the AI\nduring runtime. For this you can use the "AI Debug Display" node, which has different modes\nthat you can select to display ingame visuals for the systems of the AI.

408.description: This graph shows you how to use the "AI Random" node.
408.name: AI Random

281.commentText:
This example shows how to create a vehicle, that drives randomly throughout your level.
After creating the vehicle, just pass the vehicleId to the "AI Random" node.
The vehicle will then follow the road to the best of its abilities.
